### Enable Distributed Tracing (Node.js)

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/NEWS.md

This configuration sets distributed tracing to enabled by default in the `newrelic.js` template file supplied with the agent. This facilitates tracing requests across multiple services.

```javascript
// Inside newrelic.js
module.exports = {
  // ... other configurations
  distributed_tracing: {
    enabled: true
  }
  // ...
};
```

--------------------------------

### Retrieve Trace Metadata in Node.js

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/NEWS.md

This snippet shows how to get current Distributed Tracing span and trace IDs using the `getTraceMetadata()` method from the New Relic Node.js agent API. This information is crucial for understanding the flow of requests through distributed systems.

```javascript
const newrelic = require('newrelic');

const traceMetadata = newrelic.getTraceMetadata();
console.log(traceMetadata);
```

--------------------------------

### Enable Distributed Tracing in Node.js Agent

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/NEWS.md

This snippet shows how to enable distributed tracing in the New Relic Node.js agent. It can be configured via the `newrelic.js` file or an environment variable. Ensure you consult the transition guide before enabling.

```javascript
// In newrelic.js file:
distributed_tracing:
  enabled: true

// Or via environment variable:
NEW_RELIC_DISTRIBUTED_TRACING_ENABLED=true
```

--------------------------------

### Accept and Insert W3C Trace Context Headers in Node.js

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/NEWS.md

This snippet demonstrates how to use the New Relic Node.js agent to accept and insert W3C Trace Context headers for distributed tracing. It supports both W3C and New Relic trace header formats, simplifying agent upgrades and ensuring compatibility between different agent versions. The `distributed_tracing.exclude_newrelic_header` option can be used to disable the emission of New Relic-specific headers.

```javascript
const newrelic = require('newrelic');

// Example of accepting distributed trace headers (W3C and New Relic formats)
newrelic.TransactionHandle.prototype.acceptDistributedTraceHeaders();

// Example of inserting distributed trace headers (W3C and New Relic formats)
newrelic.Transaction.prototype.insertDistributedTraceHeaders();

// To disable emission of New Relic trace header format:
// newrelic.Transaction.prototype.insertDistributedTraceHeaders({
//   exclude_newrelic_header: true
// });
```

--------------------------------

### JavaScript Intrinsics Structure for Trace Context Testing

Source: https://github.com/newrelic/node-newrelic/blob/main/test/lib/cross_agent_tests/distributed_tracing/README.md

Demonstrates the structure for defining expected and unexpected intrinsic attributes for transaction and span events in W3C Trace Context testing. It shows how to specify common attributes applicable to all target events and specific attributes for Transaction and Span events.

```json
{
    "intrinsics": {
       "target_events": ["Transaction", "Span"],
       "common":{
         "exact": {
           "traceId": "da8bc8cc6d062849b0efcf3c169afb5a"
         },
         "expected": ["guid"],
         "unexpected": ["grandparentId"]
       },
       "Transaction": {
         "exact": {
           "parent.type": "App",
           "parent.app": "2827902",
           "parent.account": "33",
           "parent.transportType": "HTTP",
           "parentId": "e8b91a159289ff74",
           "parentSpanId": "7d3efb1b173fecfa"
         },
         "expected": ["parent.transportDuration"]
       },
       "Span": {
         "exact": {
           "parentId": "7d3efb1b173fecfa",
           "trustedParentId": "7d3efb1b173fecfa",
           "tracingVendors": ""
         },
         "expected": ["transactionId"],
         "unexpected": ["parent.transportDuration", "parent.type", "parent.app", "parent.account", "parent.transportType"]
       }
     }
   }
```

